          "body": "Verses 10-12 form the chapter's most demanding section. The command is not about comfort or long-term planning; it is about the specific moment of crisis when someone is being taken away to death (v. 11). The sage commands intervention: rescue those being led to slaughter, hold them back. The temptation being addressed is not cruelty but cowardice — the bystander's excuse of ignorance ('we did not know this,' v. 12). The sage annihilates the excuse with three rhetorical questions: Does not the God who weighs hearts know what you actually knew? Does not the God who guards your nephesh know your inaction? Will He not render to you according to your work? The weight of vv. 11-12 is significant in the canon: Proverbs 24 is among the clearest Old Testament statements of a positive duty to rescue the vulnerable — a duty that God monitors even when the social cost makes inaction attractive. Verse 10 sets the frame: if your strength is only sufficient for easy days, it is limited strength. Real koach proves itself in the day of distress."
