        "excerpt": "Do not be envious of evil men, nor desire to be with them… For there will be no future for the evil man; the lamp of the wicked will be put out.",
        "body": "The chapter's framing prohibition — stated in vv. 1-2 and repeated in vv. 19-20 — targets the most corrosive temptation wisdom literature identifies: the rational crisis produced by watching the ungodly flourish. This is not a marginal problem. Psalm 73, Psalm 37, Jeremiah 12, Habakkuk 1, and the book of Job all return to the same wound. Proverbs 24 does not sentimentalize the crisis — it frames the cure in two terse commands and grounds each one with a 'for' clause.\n\nThe first 'for' clause (v. 2) is sociological: look at what is actually in the evil man's heart (lev) and on his lips. His mind is manufacturing violence (shod — destruction, ruin); his mouth is announcing trouble (amal — toil, misery, harm). What you are envying is a person whose inner life is a violence-production engine. The company you are tempted to desire is producing harm at the level of thought and speech before it ever acts. This is Proverbs's version of Jesus's 'out of the heart' teaching (Matthew 15:19) — not a New Testament innovation but an old wisdom insight.\n\nThe second 'for' clause (v. 20) is eschatological: the evil man has no acharit — no latter end, no future trajectory that holds. His lamp (ner) will be extinguished. The lamp metaphor in Proverbs is consistently a symbol of life, lineage, and ongoing presence (cf. Prov 13:9; 20:20). Extinguishing the lamp is a way of saying that the wicked person's existence will not extend into the future — his apparent prosperity is a flame about to go out, not a sun about to rise.\n\nThe cure for envy, then, is not willpower but vision. Proverbs 24 treats envy as a problem of distorted perception: the envious person is looking at only one part of the picture — the present — and cannot see the trajectory. Lengthen the time-horizon and envy loses its logic. This is precisely the move Asaph makes in Psalm 73:17 when he enters the sanctuary and 'perceived their end.' Calvin notes on similar passages that God's people need not the suppression of their envy but its correction by a true view of the wicked's destiny.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qana* (envy, vv. 1, 19) carries the heat of jealous desire — it is the same root used for God's own jealousy for His covenant people. *Acharit* (future/latter end, vv. 14, 20) is the word Proverbs uses for life's ultimate destination. *Ner* (lamp, v. 20) — cf. Prov 13:9, where the lamp of the wicked is extinguished; 20:20, where cursing father or mother extinguishes one's lamp in deep darkness."
