        "body": "Verses 3-9 unfold wisdom's positive power in contrast to the violence the wicked devise. The household metaphor of vv. 3-4 is the chapter's most architecturally precise image. Three nouns (wisdom-chokhmah, understanding-tavunah, knowledge-daat) are distributed across three acts (built, established, filled) in a progression that is not synonymous but sequential. Chokhmah provides the original creative capacity to build at all. Tavunah (understanding, discernment — the capacity to distinguish rightly) gives it stability, making it something that holds together under load. Daat (intimate, experiential knowledge of reality) then fills the established structure with riches — the fruit of a life of disciplined engagement with reality as God has ordered it.\n\nThis triplet is Proverbs's answer to the question: what actually produces lasting wealth? Not scheme, not exploitation, not the quick gains the wicked's violence appears to produce — but the long construction of wisdom into household life. The same three nouns appear in Proverbs 3:19-20, where God Himself uses wisdom, understanding, and knowledge to found the earth, establish the heavens, and drip dew from the clouds. The sage is telling the son: the way God builds the cosmos is the way the wise man builds his house. Wisdom is not merely practical; it participates in the order by which the world was made.\n\nVerses 5-6 extend the claim into military strategy, where the payoff seems most counterintuitive. A wise man is strong (oz — strength, might); knowledge increases koach. The military example (v. 6) is not decorative: in a world where physical force is the most visible form of power, Proverbs insists that wise guidance (tachbulah — steering, like a ship's ropes guiding a rudder) and a multitude of counselors produce victory that raw force alone cannot. This is the same counsel that 1 Kings 12 illustrates negatively: Rehoboam's rejection of the wise counselors in favor of the young hotheads produces the kingdom's fracture. The claim of Proverbs 24:6 is historical wisdom, not wishful idealism.\n\nVerses 7-9 close the section with the negative portraits: the fool (evil) cannot access wisdom — it is too high (rum, exalted above his reach), so he has nothing to contribute in the gate. The schemer (baal mezimmot, v. 8 — literally 'master of schemes') is publicly labeled for what he is. The scoffer (luts) is an abomination (toevah) — the same word used for what God most rejects. The word toevah appears in Proverbs 17 times and is never used lightly; it marks what God finds morally repulsive.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tavunah* (understanding, v. 3) is related to *bin* — to discern between things. *Tachbulah* (guidance, v. 6) is from the root for rope or cable — it is the word for the steering of a ship. *Toevah* (abomination, v. 9) is the same word used in Deuteronomy for idolatry and in Proverbs repeatedly for what perverts justice."
