        "title": "Honest judgment, honest speech, sequenced labor — wisdom's public and practical demands",
        "range": "24:23-34",
        "excerpt": "Prove yourselves doers of the word, and not merely hearers who delude themselves… Then your poverty will come as a robber and your want like an armed man.",
        "body": "The appendix of vv. 23-34 (introduced as 'also sayings of the wise,' v. 23) applies wisdom to three concrete domains: judicial integrity, honest speech, and productive labor. The judicial section (vv. 23-25) opens with the bluntest possible statement: partiality in judgment is not good (tov). The simplicity of the verdict conceals its severity — 'not good' in wisdom literature often understates what is in fact a serious moral failure. The judge who says to the wicked 'you are righteous' (tsaddiq — the very word the wicked is not) earns cursing from peoples and abhorrence from nations. The international scope of the verdict is significant: perverted justice is not merely a local problem but a corruption that damages the fabric of civil society everywhere it occurs. Those who rebuke the wicked, by contrast, receive delight and good blessing — the two greatest social goods wisdom promises.\n\nVerse 26 offers one of Proverbs's most intimate metaphors: an honest answer is like a kiss on the lips. The word translated 'right answer' is nakhoach — straightforward, direct, without deviousness. The kiss metaphor is not romantic but relational: in the ancient Near East, the kiss was an act of greeting, loyalty, and genuine affection (cf. 1 Samuel 20:41; Romans 16:16). A straight answer given at the right moment is as intimate and welcome as that gesture — it draws people together rather than creating distance. This places honest speech in the register of love, not merely duty.\n\nVerse 27 presents wisdom's sequencing principle: prepare your outdoor work and make it ready in the field; afterwards, build your house. The agricultural order is practical — in an agrarian economy, the field must be producing before the house is expanded, because the field's produce funds the household. But the principle generalizes: wisdom requires that productive capacity be established before domestic comfort is expanded. The temptation to build the house first (to expand comfort before establishing income) is the same temptation the sluggard poem will close with — the preference of rest over preparation.\n\nThe sluggard narrative (vv. 30-34) is the chapter's literary climax. The sage walks past, observes, reflects, and receives instruction — the three verbs of v. 32 (chazah — to gaze; shit lev — to take to heart; laqach musar — to receive discipline/instruction) are themselves a model of the inductive method. Looking at what is actually there, bringing the observation into the heart, and allowing it to form you: this is how wisdom is acquired. The scene observed — thorns, nettles, a broken stone wall — is the outer record of inner choices. Douglas Moo's observation (applied to the New Testament) that the physical world is morally revelatory applies here too: the ruined field does not lie about the character of its keeper. The poverty that arrives (v. 34) is not an injustice visited on the sluggard; it is the natural outcome of what he chose, arriving with the force and finality of an armed robber.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nakhoach* (honest/right, v. 26) — straight, direct, without crookedness. *Nashaq* (kiss, v. 26) — the greeting of loyalty and affection. *Musar* (instruction/discipline, v. 32) — the same word used across Proverbs for the discipline that wisdom imparts; it carries the sense of corrective formation, not merely information. *Resh* (poverty, v. 34) and *machsor* (want/lack) — the two words for material destitution that Proverbs pairs consistently to describe the sluggard's end."
